<h4 id="quick">Quick one-liners</h4>

<h5>Paste an inline string</h5>
{{ call .Highlight `curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=Hello, world!" \
  -F "syntax=plaintext"` "bash" }}

<h5>Paste a text file (body as field value)</h5>
{{ call .Highlight `curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=<myfile.txt" \
  -F "syntax=autodetect" \
  -F "title=myfile.txt"` "bash" }}

<h5>Upload a binary file / image</h5>
{{ call .Highlight `curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "file=@screenshot.png"` "bash" }}

<h5>Get just the paste URL — with jq</h5>
{{ call .Highlight `curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -H "Accept: application/json" \
  -F "body=Hello" \
  | jq -r '.data.url'` "bash" }}

<h5>Get just the paste URL — without jq (plain-text response)</h5>
<p>curl is detected as a non-interactive client; omitting <code>Accept: application/json</code>
returns a plain-text response that needs no JSON parsing:</p>
{{ call .Highlight `curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=Hello" \
  | grep '^url:' | cut -d' ' -f2` "bash" }}


<h4 id="stdin">Pipe from stdin</h4>

<p>The key is <code>-F "body=&lt;-"</code>. The <code>&lt;-</code> syntax tells curl to read the
<em>field value</em> from stdin — not as a file attachment, just as the paste body. Every tool
that writes to stdout feeds directly into this:</p>

{{ call .Highlight `# Paste any command output
ls -la | curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=<-" -F "syntax=autodetect" | jq -r '.data.url'

# Paste a log tail
tail -100 /var/log/syslog | curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=<-" -F "syntax=syslog" | jq -r '.data.url'

# Paste git diff with syntax highlighting
git diff | curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=<-" -F "syntax=diff" | jq -r '.data.url'

# Paste compiler / test output
cargo test 2>&1 | curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=<-" -F "syntax=plaintext" | jq -r '.data.url'

# Redirect a file (same as -F "body=<file.txt")
curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=<-" -F "syntax=autodetect" < myfile.txt | jq -r '.data.url'` "bash" }}

<p><strong>Without jq</strong> — omit <code>Accept: application/json</code> and parse the plain-text reply:</p>
{{ call .Highlight `git diff | curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "body=<-" -F "syntax=diff" \
  | grep '^url:' | cut -d' ' -f2` "bash" }}


<h4 id="files">File &amp; image upload</h4>

<p>Use <code>-F "file=@path"</code> to upload a file as a binary multipart attachment. Works for
any file type: text, images, PDFs, archives. The server stores the file binary-safely and returns
it with the correct MIME type on download.</p>

{{ call .Highlight `# Upload an image
curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "file=@screenshot.png" | jq -r '.data.url'

# Upload a PDF
curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "file=@report.pdf" | jq -r '.data.url'

# Upload with a custom title and 1-hour expiry
curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "file=@diagram.svg" \
  -F "title=Architecture Diagram" \
  -F "expiration=3600" | jq -r '.data.url'

# Capture a screenshot and upload in one step (Linux — requires scrot)
scrot /tmp/snap.png && curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "file=@/tmp/snap.png" | jq -r '.data.url'

# macOS screenshot upload
screencapture -x /tmp/snap.png && curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -F "file=@/tmp/snap.png" | jq -r '.data.url'` "bash" }}

<p><strong>Difference between <code>file=@path</code> and <code>body=&lt;path</code>:</strong></p>
<table>
	<tr>
		<th>Form field</th>
		<th>Best for</th>
		<th>How it is stored</th>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><code>file=@path</code></td>
		<td>Binary files, images, any file type</td>
		<td>Binary attachment — served back with original MIME type</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><code>body=&lt;path</code></td>
		<td>Plain-text files only</td>
		<td>Raw text — syntax-highlighted when viewed in the browser</td>
	</tr>
</table>


<h4 id="json">JSON body</h4>

<p>Send <code>Content-Type: application/json</code> to POST a JSON object instead of form fields.
Pair with <code>Accept: application/json</code> to receive a JSON response.</p>

{{ call .Highlight `# Simple JSON paste
curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Accept: application/json" \
  -d '{"title":"My paste","body":"Hello, world!","syntax":"plaintext"}' \
  | jq -r '.data.url'

# Pipe stdin through jq to build the JSON payload (handles escaping automatically)
cat myfile.py | jq -Rs '{"body":.,"syntax":"python","title":"script.py"}' \
  | curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
       -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
       -H "Accept: application/json" \
       --data-binary @- \
  | jq -r '.data.url'

# Burn-after-reading paste (deleted on first view)
curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Accept: application/json" \
  -d '{"body":"secret token","oneUse":true,"expiration":600}' \
  | jq -r '.data.url'

# Private paste with author metadata
curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Accept: application/json" \
  -d '{"body":"private content","private":true,"author":"Alice","authorURL":"https://alice.example.com"}' \
  | jq -r '.data.url'` "bash" }}

<p>See <a href="/docs/apiv1#create">API v1 reference</a> for the full list of JSON fields.</p>


<h4 id="retrieve">Retrieve a paste</h4>

{{ call .Highlight `# Get by ID — query param
curl -sS "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes?id=XcmX9ON1" | jq -r '.data.body'

# Get by ID — path style (equivalent)
curl -sS "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes/XcmX9ON1" | jq -r '.data.body'

# Raw body as plain text (no JSON wrapping)
curl -sS "$CASPASTE_URL/XcmX9ON1/raw"

# Download a file paste with its original filename
curl -sS -OJ "$CASPASTE_URL/XcmX9ON1/raw"

# List recent pastes
curl -sS "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" | jq '.[].id'` "bash" }}


<h4 id="bash-zsh">Bash / Zsh function</h4>

<p>Add to <code>~/.bashrc</code>, <code>~/.zshrc</code>, or <code>~/.bash_profile</code>.
After sourcing, any pipe can end with <code>| paste</code>.</p>

{{ call .Highlight `# ── CasPaste shell function ─────────────────────────────────
paste() {
  local url="${CASPASTE_URL:-https://your-server}"
  local syntax="${CASPASTE_SYNTAX:-autodetect}"
  local title="${CASPASTE_TITLE:-}"
  local result

  if [ "${1:-}" = "--help" ] || [ "${1:-}" = "-h" ]; then
    printf 'Usage:\n'
    printf '  paste [file]        Upload a file (text or binary)\n'
    printf '  paste "text"        Paste an inline string\n'
    printf '  cat file | paste    Paste from stdin\n'
    printf '  cmd  | paste        Paste command output\n'
    printf '\nEnvironment variables:\n'
    printf '  CASPASTE_URL     Server base URL (required)\n'
    printf '  CASPASTE_SYNTAX  Syntax hint, default: autodetect\n'
    printf '  CASPASTE_TITLE   Default title\n'
    return 0
  fi

  if [ -n "${1:-}" ] && [ -f "$1" ]; then
    # File argument — binary-safe multipart upload
    result=$(curl -sS -X POST "$url/api/v1/pastes" \
      -H "Accept: application/json" \
      -F "file=@$1" \
      -F "syntax=$syntax" \
      ${title:+-F "title=$title"})
  elif [ -n "${1:-}" ]; then
    # Inline text argument
    result=$(curl -sS -X POST "$url/api/v1/pastes" \
      -H "Accept: application/json" \
      -F "body=$1" \
      -F "syntax=$syntax" \
      ${title:+-F "title=$title"})
  else
    # Stdin — works with pipes and redirects
    result=$(curl -sS -X POST "$url/api/v1/pastes" \
      -H "Accept: application/json" \
      -F "body=<-" \
      -F "syntax=$syntax" \
      ${title:+-F "title=$title"})
  fi

  if command -v jq >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    printf '%s\n' "$result" | jq -r '.data.url // .error // "upload failed"'
  else
    printf '%s\n' "$result" | grep -o '"url":"[^"]*"' | cut -d'"' -f4
  fi
}
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────` "bash" }}

<h5>Usage examples</h5>
{{ call .Highlight `# Set your server
export CASPASTE_URL=https://your-server

# Pipe command output
git diff | paste
ls -la | paste
cat /var/log/syslog | paste

# Upload a file
paste myfile.py
paste screenshot.png

# Inline text
paste "quick note"

# Override syntax or title inline
CASPASTE_SYNTAX=go paste main.go
CASPASTE_TITLE="Today's log" paste < app.log` "bash" }}


<h4 id="fish">Fish function</h4>

<p>Save as <code>~/.config/fish/functions/paste.fish</code> — fish auto-loads it.</p>

{{ call .Highlight `# ~/.config/fish/functions/paste.fish
function paste --description "Upload to CasPaste"
    set -q CASPASTE_URL;    or set -l CASPASTE_URL    "https://your-server"
    set -q CASPASTE_SYNTAX; or set -l CASPASTE_SYNTAX "autodetect"
    set -q CASPASTE_TITLE;  or set -l CASPASTE_TITLE  ""

    set -l result

    if test (count $argv) -gt 0; and test -f $argv[1]
        # File argument — binary-safe multipart upload
        set result (curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
          -H "Accept: application/json" \
          -F "file=@$argv[1]" \
          -F "syntax=$CASPASTE_SYNTAX")
    else if test (count $argv) -gt 0
        # Inline text argument
        set result (curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
          -H "Accept: application/json" \
          -F "body=$argv[1]" \
          -F "syntax=$CASPASTE_SYNTAX")
    else
        # Stdin — works with pipes
        set result (curl -sS -X POST "$CASPASTE_URL/api/v1/pastes" \
          -H "Accept: application/json" \
          -F "body=<-" \
          -F "syntax=$CASPASTE_SYNTAX")
    end

    if command -q jq
        echo $result | jq -r '.data.url // .error // "upload failed"'
    else
        echo $result | string match -rg '"url":"([^"]+)"'
    end
end` "bash" }}

<h5>Usage examples</h5>
{{ call .Highlight `# Set your server (add to ~/.config/fish/config.fish)
set -x CASPASTE_URL https://your-server

# Pipe command output
git diff | paste
cat /var/log/syslog | paste

# Upload a file
